    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-08-20T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-08-20T09:00:00-05:00" n="163"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d163">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/6540</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Sweden</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1917Supp02v01#p_MIN1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morris</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stockholm</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-08-20T15:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 20, 1917, 3 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received August 21, 5.30 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>652. Had long conference to-day with <persName
                        corresp="frus1917Supp02v01#p_LAAA1">Admiral Lindman</persName>, Minister for
                    Foreign Affairs. <persName corresp="frus1917Supp02v01#p_LAAA1"
                        >Lindman</persName> discussed at length Sweden’s position as regards imports
                    from America. He stated that Sweden was in urgent need of certain articles which
                    are absolute necessities but added that for economic reasons Sweden could never
                    agree entirely <pb facs="0285" n="1039" xml:id="pg_1039"/> to discontinue
                    exports to Germany. He pointed out however that during May and June only two
                    thousand head of cattle were exported from Sweden to Germany.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="frus1917Supp02v01#p_LAAA1">Lindman</persName> … states that
                    this year’s crops in Germany are good and that he even has hopes that there will
                    be a surplus of grain as well as of mineral oil which can be exported to Sweden.
                    I queried <persName corresp="frus1917Supp02v01#p_LAAA1">Lindman</persName> as to
                    the proposed neutral conference at Stockholm, see my 620. He stated that it had
                    nothing to do with the effect upon neutral countries of America’s entry into the
                    war. That this conference had nothing to do with peace negotiations but that it
                    was called to discuss the question of the rights and interests of neutral
                    countries after the close of the war.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1917Supp02v01#p_MIN1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Morris</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
